As @Logo_Daedalus is gone, and summer is upon us, I will drop some Logoesque seasonal takes, paraphrasing his beloved Frye. Summer is time of great romance, when dreams come true, the time of the Magic Mountain of Mann. Things do not "change", but are fulfilled and experienced.

One central quest reigns in the middle of summer: a quest that is established at the beginning of the story.

It is good to make plans about summer at the start of the season, now, and then proceed to fulfill them.
all of my posts are
come on bro you already know

The summer hero is of an upper world, and proceeds to descend into the lower one. The suburban friend going to the sleazy beach club, the downtown rooftop bar.

The hero is solar and divine in participation in the myth, and very much manlike in romance. "Hey", says the simple DM.

The primary enemy of the hero is sterility. The dragon that sucked the life from the land, that Perseus needs to slay.

A girl suffers in that barren field, and awaits being saved. And in summer, saving her always is a successful endeavour.

The bride-figure is ambiguous: she is always in the forbidden place. She is rescued from behind the wall, from the bottom of the well, the thorns.

The quest-romance is the triumph of fertility over sterility. The defeat of the dragon.

The hero is wounded and weakened many times, but is strengthened by the drinking of water and the tree of life.

Romance is dialectical. Every character and hero has his opposite counterpart, black and white, and they walk the same path, starting from the opposite sides of it.

A final element: the connection between the earth and the sun. A lighthouse, a ladder, a mountain that needs to be climbed. In summer, the relation between the ground, on which we step with bare feet, and sun, that shines on our bodies, is made apparent.

Mountains can be climbed, rooftops can be contemplated, elevators leading up and down rail-cruise on their mysterious journey. You can descend down, but later you can climb up to the light.

May this thread make at least one single person's summer more meaningful and better.
